Introduction¶

Dataset Description¶

Tip: This data set describes info about 10,000 movies collected from TMDb(The Movie Datbase, including movie actors, directors, budget, revenue, runtime(duration), ..., and etc.
This data set contains:
-10867 rows
-21 columns

Question(s) for Analysis¶

01: Which genres are most produced?
02: Top 20 directors who directes most movies?
03: Top 20 actors who acted in films?
04: Top 20 production compaines with higher releases?
05: Top&lower 10 movies in budget, revenue, profit, rating, popularity?
06: Which year&month has the most releases?
07: which year&month has the higher revenue?
08: What is the average of budget, revenue, profit for each year?
09: What is the type of correlation between Revenue and Popularity, Rating, Runtime?
10: What is the type of correlation between Runtime and Budget, Revenue, Profit, Rating?

# If filter by year needed
def year_filter(df, filter_from=None, filter_to=None):
    """
    Filters our data frame respect to specific years.

    INPUT:
        df (Optional): pandas.DataFrame
            data to filter it.
        filter_from (Optional): int
            value to start filter from it, if None then no lower limit will be applied.
        filter_to (optional): int
            value to stop filter to it, if None the no upper limit will be apllied.
    OUTPUT:
        filterd data frame by given limits.
    """

    # If no limits were given
    if not filter_from and not filter_to:
        # No filter
        return df
    # If lower limit was given
    elif filter_from and not filter_to:
        # Apply filter
        df = df[filter_from <= df["release_year"]]
        pass
    # If upper limit was given
    elif not filter_from and filter_to:
        # Apply filter
        df = df[df["release_year"] <= filter_to]
        pass
    # If both limits were given
    else:
        # If lower limit is greater from the upper, then awap them
        if filter_from > filter_to:
            filter_from, filter_to = filter_to, filter_from
        # Apply filter
        df = df[df["release_year"].between(filter_from, filter_to)]
    return df
df = year_filter(df)

Question 1 (Which genres are most produced?)¶

In [25]:
# Because that director and genres has many values, i found that if complex rows splitted
# it will cause a lot of duplicates in data raw,so I've chosen to isolate splitted(single) data values.
def complex_in_year(df, column):
    """
    Function gets all complex data column in each year.
    INPUT:
        df: pandas.DataFrame
            Source of data to get complex data in year
        column: str
            complex column name to split
    OUTPUT: pandas.DataFrame
        dataframe of years and extracted data from column
    """
    if column not in df.columns:
        return None
    # get all unique years.
    years = df["release_year"].unique()
    # sort years ascending.
    years.sort()

    # Empty dataframe to values inside.
    result_df = pd.DataFrame(columns=["release_year", column, "vote_average"])

    # loop over years.
    for year in years:
        # get column and vote average data in the current year
        release_year_filter = df.query("release_year == {}".format(year))[
            [column, "vote_average"]
        ]
        for year_genre, year_vote in zip(
            release_year_filter[column], release_year_filter["vote_average"]
        ):
            # Split each column data in row.
            for value in year_genre.split("|"):
                # Add splitted values from row in the year.
                result_df = result_df.append(
                    {"release_year": year, column: value, "vote_average": year_vote},
                    ignore_index=True,
                )
    return result_df

Conclusions¶

  • The most directed genres are drama, comedy, thriller.
  • Top 3 directors who directed movies are Woody Allen, Clint Eastwood, and Steven spielberg.
  • Top 3 actors who filmed movies are Robert De Niro, Samuel L.Jackson, and Bruce Wills.
  • Higher 3 production companies in movies production are Universal Pictures, Warner Bros, and Paramount Pictures.
  • 2014 is the most year has releases by 635 movies. And Sep is the most month has releases by 1203 movies
  • 2015 is the most year has revenue, and Jun is the most month you able to get higher revenue in it.
  • 'Avatar', 'Star Wars: The Force Awakens', and 'Titanic' are the most movies got profit.
  • Profit is in strong correlation with revenue.
  • Vote count in movies is strong correlated with popularity, profit, and revenue.
  • Long movies duration are mostly common, and affects profit positively.

Limitations¶

While cleaning data I removed unused columns, and in columns that contain '|' separated values I've chosen to split them into different files to avoid data duplicates in the main CSV file.

This project is still not perfectly solved because I think that we should remove outliers by reprocessing our data, also because of my lack of experience.
